SIMPLE: wise
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wise
<hw>Wise</hw> <pr>(w⟦imac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Wiser</adjf>
<pr>(w⟦imac⟧z"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Wisest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wis</ets>, AS.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧s</ets>; akin to OS. & OFries. <ets>w⟦imac⟧s</ets>, D.
<ets>wijs</ets>, G. <ets>weise</ets>, OHG. <ets>w⟦imac⟧s</ets>,
<ets>w⟦imac⟧si</ets>, Icel. <ets>v⟦imac⟧ss</ets>, Sw. <ets>vis</ets>,
Dan. <ets>viis</ets>, Goth. <ets>weis</ets>; akin to <ets>wit</ets>, v.
i. See <er>Wit</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and cf. <er>Righteous</er>,
<er>Wisdom</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having knowledge; knowing; enlightened; of extensive
information; erudite; learned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are <qex>wise</qex> to do evil, but to do good they have no
knowledge.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. iv. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, especially, making due use of knowledge;
discerning and judging soundly concerning what is true or false, proper
or improper; choosing the best ends and the best means for accomplishing
them; sagacious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When clouds appear, <qex>wise</qex> men put their cloaks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From a child thou hast known the holy scriptures, which are able
to make thee <qex>wise</qex> unto salvation.</q> <rj><qau>2 Tim. iii.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Versed in art or science; skillful; dexterous;
specifically, skilled in divination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qperson>Fal.</qperson> There was, mine host, an old fat woman
even now with me; but she's gone.⟦br⟧
<qperson>Sim.</qperson> Pray you, sir, was't not the <qex>wise</qex>
woman of Brentford?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, prudent; calculating; shrewd; wary; subtle;
crafty.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou art . . . no novice, but a
governor wily and <xex>wise</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor, on the other side,⟦br⟧
Will I be penuriously <qex>wise</qex>⟦br⟧
<qex>As to make money</qex>, <qex>that's my slave</qex>, <qex>my
idol</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lords do not care for me:⟦br⟧
I am too <qex>wise</qex> to die yet.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Dictated or guided by wisdom; containing or
exhibiting wisdom; well adapted to produce good effects; judicious;
discreet; <as>as, a <ex>wise</ex> saying; a <ex>wise</ex> scheme or
plan; <ex>wise</ex> conduct or management; a <ex>wise</ex>
determination</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Eminent in <xex>wise</xex>
deport.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To make it wise</b></col>, <cd>to make it a matter of
deliberation.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧We thought it was not
worth <xex>to make it wise</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au> --
<col><b>Wise in years</b></col>, <cd>old enough to be wise; wise from
age and experience; hence, aged; old.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A very grave, state bachelor, my dainty one;⟦br⟧
He's <qex>wise in years</qex>, and of a temperate warmth.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are too <qex>wise in years</qex>, too full of counsel,⟦br⟧
For my green experience.</q> <rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>wise</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: wise
<hw>wise</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wise</ets>, AS.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧se</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>w⟦imac⟧sa</ets>, OFries.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧s</ets>, D. <ets>wijs</ets>, <ets>wijze</ets>, OHG.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧sa</ets>, G. <ets>weise</ets>, Sw. <ets>vis</ets>, Dan.
<ets>viis</ets>, Icel. ⟦oum⟧⟦edh⟧ru<ets>v⟦imac⟧s</ets> otherwise; from
the root of E. <ets>wit</ets>; hence, originally, knowledge, skill. See
<er>Wit</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and cf. <er>Guise</er>.]</ety> <def>Way of
being or acting; manner; mode; fashion.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All armed in
complete <xex>wise</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To love her in my beste <qex>wyse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This song she sings in most commanding <qex>wise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not these blessings then, sent from above,⟦br⟧
Abused be, or spilt in profane <qex>wise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word is nearly obsolete, except in such phrases as
<xex>in any wise</xex>, <xex>in no wise</xex>, <xex>on this wise</xex>,
etc. ⟦ldquo⟧ Fret not thyself <xex>in any wise</xex> to do evil.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Ps. xxxvii. 8.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧He shall <xex>in no wise</xex> lose his
reward.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Matt. x. 42.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>On this wise</xex> ye
shall bless the children of Israel.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Num. vi.
23.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Wise</xex> is often used as a suffix in
composition, as in like<xex>wise</xex>, no<xex>wise</xex>,
length<xex>wise</xex>, etc., in which words <xex>-ways</xex> is often
substituted with the same sense; as, no<xex>ways</xex>,
length<xex>ways</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wiseacre</ent>⟦br⟧
